AIM:

To build a Student CRUD application using Spring Boot. Map the database table using JPA annotations such as @Entity, @Id, @Table, and @Column, and perform Create, Read, Update, and Delete (CRUD) operations using a relational database.

PROCEDURE:

Create a Spring Boot project using Spring Initializr.

Add the required dependencies:

Spring Web
Spring Data JPA
MySQL Driver (or H2 Database)

Create a package (example: com.spring.student).

Create a class Student and annotate it using:

@Entity
@Table
@Id
@Column

Create a Repository interface using JpaRepository to perform CRUD operations.

Create a Service class to handle business logic.

Create a Controller class to accept user requests.

Configure the database connection in application.properties.

Run the application and test CRUD operations using a browser or Postman.

CODE:
Student.java (Entity Class)
package com.spring.student;

import jakarta.persistence.Entity;
import jakarta.persistence.Id;
import jakarta.persistence.Table;
import jakarta.persistence.Column;

@Entity
@Table(name = "student")
public class Student {

    @Id
    @Column(name = "student_id")
    private int id;

    @Column(name = "student_name")
    private String name;

    @Column(name = "department")
    private String department;

    public Student() {
    }

    public Student(int id, String name, String department) {
        this.id = id;
        this.name = name;
        this.department = department;
    }

    public int getId() {
        return id;
    }

    public void setId(int id) {
        this.id = id;
    }

    public String getName() {
        return name;
    }

    public void setName(String name) {
        this.name = name;
    }

    public String getDepartment() {
        return department;
    }

    public void setDepartment(String department) {
        this.department = department;
    }
}
